<p>Think of Disney, I mean, Disney is selling, will say, home video onâ€¦I donâ€™t knowâ€¦whateverâ€¦ $ 16.95, $18.95 or whatever. All over the world, people, and we will say particularly, mothers in this case, have something in their mind about Disney. I mean, every person in this room, when you say Disney, have something in their mind about it. If I say Universal Pictures you donâ€™t have anything (special) in your mind, you know. If I say 20th Century Fox, you donâ€™t have anything special in your mind. But if I say Disney, you got something in your mind. Thatâ€™s true around the world. Now picture yourself with a couple of young kids, you know, who you want to put away a couple of hours every day, when you get old, to get peace of mind. you know if you get them one video they will watch it 20 times. So you go to the video store where you buy the videos. Are you gonna sit there and premier, you know, 10 different videos and watch each for an hour and half after to decide which one your kids should watch? No. I mean, letâ€™s say there is one there for $16.95 and in the Disney there itâ€™s $17.95. You know if you take the Disney video, you gonna be OK! So you buy it. You donâ€™t have to make a quality decision on something that you donâ€™t want to spend the time to do. So you can get a little bit more money if youâ€™re Disney, and you will sell a lot more videos. It makes it a wonderful business. It makes it very tough for the other guys. How would you try to create a brand â€“ Dreamworks is trying â€“ but how would you try to create a brand that competes with Disney around the world and to replace the concept that people have in their minds about Disney with something, say, Universal Pictures? So the motherâ€™s gonna walk in and pick up the Universal Pictures video and preference to Disney? Itâ€™s not gonna happen.</p>

