<p>Buffett: The question is about my business mistakes or how much time do you have. The interesting thing about business is this: in investments â€“ at least for me and for my partner Charlie Munger â€“ the biggest mistakes have not been mistakes of commission but theyâ€™ve been mistakes of omission where we knew enough about the business to do something. For one reason or another, we sat there sucking our thumbs instead of doing something. Weâ€™ve passed up things where could have made billions and billions of dollars from things we understood. Forget about things we donâ€™t understand. The fact that I can make billions from Microsoft but it doesnâ€™t mean anything because I never understand Microsoft. But I can make billions out of healthcare stocks and we should have made it. I didnâ€™t. When the Clinton healthcare program was proposed and they all went in the tank, we shouldâ€™ve made a ton of money out of that because I can understand it. I didnâ€™t make it. I should have made a ton of money out of Fannie Mae back in the mid-eighties. I understood it and I didnâ€™t do it. Those are billion-dollar mistakes â€“ or multibillion dollars mistakes â€“ that the Generally Accepted Accounting Principles donâ€™t pick up.</p>

