<p>You can learn something, perhaps from the mistakesâ€¦ the big thing you should do is to stick with businesses you understand. So there is a generic mistake of getting outside of your circle of competence. You know, buying something because somebody tips you off or something of the sort in an area you donâ€™t really think aboutâ€¦you should learn something from that. You should stay with what you can figure out yourself. You really want your decision-making to beâ€¦by looking in a mirror. Saying to yourself: â€œIâ€™m buying 100 shares of General Motors at 55 becauseâ€¦â€ itâ€™s your responsibility if you are buying it. Itâ€™s gotta be a reason. If you canâ€™t state the reason, you shouldnâ€™t buy it. Because somebody told you at a cocktail party? Not good enough. Itâ€™s gotta be somethingâ€¦you knowâ€¦it canâ€™t be because the volume, the chart looks good, or anything like that. Itâ€™s gotta be a reason you buy the business. Thatâ€¦we stick to it very carefully. Thatâ€™s one of the things Ben Graham had taught me.</p>

