<p>The real question is whether we can keep retaining dollar bills and turning them into more than a dollar at a decent rate. Thatâ€™s we try to do. Charlie Munger and I all have our money in to do that. Thatâ€™s all we will get paid for doing it. We wonâ€™t take any options. We wonâ€™t take any salaries. We donâ€™t pick up anything. We ride around the plane. Thatâ€™s what we are trying to do. It gets harder all the time. The more money we manage the harder it is to do that. We would do way better percentage wise with Berkshire if it is 1/100 the present size. It is run for its owners. But it isnâ€™t run to give them dividend. Because, so far, every dollar that weâ€™ve earned and could have paid out, we have turned into more than a dollar. It worth more than a dollar to keep it. It would be silly to pay out, even if everybody is tax-free to own it. It would have been a mistake to pay dividends of Berkshire because so far the dollar bills retained have turned into more than a dollar. There is no guarantee that that will happen in the future. At some point the game runs out on that. But itâ€™s the goal. I mean, thatâ€™s what the business is about. We are notâ€¦nothing else about the business do we judge ourselves by. We donâ€™t judge by the size of the home office building or, you know, anything of the number of people working around it. We got 12 people at headquarters, we got 45,000 employees at Berkshire. 12 people at headquarter, 3,500 square feet and we wonâ€™t change it. We will judge ourselves by the performance of the company. Thatâ€™s the only way we will get paid. But, believe me, it is a lot harder than it used to be.</p>

