<p>New York Stock Exchange is a big supermarket of companies. You are going to buying stocks. What do you want it to happen? You want those stocks to go down, way down. And you will make better buys then. Later on, 20 years from now, 30 years from now, you are in the period when you dis-saving, or lairs dis-saving for you then you gotâ€¦ I mean, then you may care about higher prices. But I find peopleâ€¦ that was one of theâ€¦ thatâ€™s chapter 8 in Ben Grahamâ€™s â€œintelligent investorâ€ about the attitude toward stock market fluctuations. That and chapter 20 on the â€œmargin of safetyâ€ are the two most important essays ever written on investing as far as I concern. Because when I read chapter 8 when I was 18, I figured, you know, I just figured out what I just said butâ€¦ it is obvious, but I didnâ€™t figure out myself though. It was explained to me. I probably would have gone another 100 years if I hadnâ€™t  read it. I would still thought it was good when my stocks were going up.</p>

